  <!-- Educational Article -->
  <section class="max-w-[760px] w-full mx-auto px-4 pb-20 flex flex-col gap-8 text-slate print:hidden" aria-labelledby="about-tool-heading">
    <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <h2 id="about-tool-heading" class="font-display font-semibold text-xl sm:text-2xl text-primary tracking-tight">
        Reference Tuning Pitch & Acoustic Tuning Fork Engine
      </h2>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        An acoustic <strong>tuning fork</strong> is an acoustic resonator in the form of a two-pronged fork with the prongs formed from a U-shaped U-bar of elastic metal (usually steel). When struck against a surface, it vibrates at a specific constant frequency, emitting a pure musical tone. Tuning forks are widely used to tune musical instruments, calibrate scientific sound equipment, and test hearing capacity.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        Equal Temperament Math & Audio Synthesizer
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Modern Western music relies on <strong>twelve-tone equal temperament (12-TET)</strong>. In this tuning system, the octave is divided into twelve log-linear intervals called semitones. The frequency $f$ of any note is calculated relative to a reference note (typically A4, calibrated at 440 Hz) using the mathematical formula:
      </p>
      <div class="bg-surface border border-hairline rounded-xl p-4 my-2 text-center">
        <code class="font-mono text-xs text-primary font-semibold">
          Frequency (Hz) = A4_Ref_Hz * 2^(semitones_from_A4 / 12)
        </code>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Our digital Tuning Fork engine applies standard AudioContext synthesis to generate this pure sine wave, ensuring 100% mathematical pitch accuracy. By altering the calibrated A4 reference frequency (e.g. down to 432 Hz or baroque 415 Hz), the relative frequencies of all note choices dynamically adjust in real time.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

